  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The preprint titled \"Electrostatic encoding of genome organization principles within single native nucleosomes\" has made a significant impact, garnering 25 citations and has successfully transitioned to formal publication in a peer-reviewed journal, demonstrating its scientific relevance. Key institutions such as Bloomberg, Washington University in St. Louis, and Princeton University showcase the strong academic backing of this research, which explores pivotal aspects of genome organization.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work by Sangwoo Park and colleagues presents groundbreaking findings on how electrostatic properties encode genome organization principles within nucleosomes. The discussion is underscored by its substantial academic footprint, reflected in 25 citations from sources including bioRxiv and The EMBO Journal. This early sharing has effectively positioned the research at the forefront of discussions in structural biology and biochemistry.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The study has successfully transitioned from preprint status to formal publication, further validating its findings within the academic community. The combined impact of both the preprint and the final published version, which has accumulated an additional 18 citations since publication, reflects a robust interest in the identified principles of nucleosome organization. Such metrics are indicative of the research fueling ongoing exploration in the field.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Institutions such as Bloomberg, Washington University in St. Louis, and Princeton University highlight the quality and credibility of the research environment supporting this work. The citations originate not only from the United States but also from Japan, China, and France, indicating a broad geographic interest and academic engagement with the findings.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, the commitment to open science is exemplified through the early sharing of the preprint, which has catalyzed immediate community engagement, facilitating dialogue within the scientific community even before formal publication. The work exemplifies a significant contribution to our understanding of nucleosome dynamics, further encouraging future inquiries into genome organization.</p>",
